Geography:
Cameroon is divided into four distinct topographical regions:
(a) in the south there is a low coastal plain covered with equatorial rain forests;
(b) in the centre there is a transitional plateau which rises to the north to the Adamaoua Mountains;
(c) to the west there are mountain forests peaking in Mt. Cameroon (4,050 m);
(d) to the north of Adamaoua range, rolling savanna slopes gradually down to the marshlands surrounding Lake Chad.
The climate is as varied as the topography but tends to grade from equatorial-humid in the south to Sahelian-arid in the north. In the south there is a prolonged and heavy rainy season which is at its most intense from June to September. The uplands have less rain and two peaks in April and October.

CommentFresh:
